title: $:/plugins/crosseye/simple-outline/usage
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

!! Create Outline

Once you've installed `simple-outline` to your TiddlyWiki 5.3.0+ wiki and saved, you can create an outline tiddler and use the widget:

```
<$simple-outline text={{MyOutlineTiddler}} class="outline"/>
```

Or supply the outline text inline:

```
<$simple-outline text="""
!! Section heading

  Group label
    + tiddler-name
    + display text :: tiddler-title
""" class="outline"/>
```

!! Input Format

Each line of the `text` attribute describes one node:

|!Syntax |!Meaning |
|`!! Heading` |Section header — renders as `<h2>` |
|`+ tiddler-name` |Tiddler reference — expands to show its body if it exists |
|`display text :: tiddler-name` |Same, with an explicit label instead of the tiddler title |
|Plain text |Structural group — collapsible if it has children |
|Indentation |Each extra indent level (leading spaces) is one nesting level deeper |

For tiddler references, the displayed label comes from the first of these fields that exists on the tiddler: `summary` → `caption` → the name as written.

!! Attributes

|!Attribute |!Default |!Purpose |
|`text` |— |The outline description (required) |
|`class` |`outline` |CSS class(es) added to the container `<div>` |
|`summary-template` |— |Tiddler rendered inside each `<summary>` element; receives `currentTiddler` and `so-label` |
|`detail-template` |— |Tiddler rendered as the expanded body for each tiddler item; receives `currentTiddler` and `so-label` |

!! CSS Hooks

The plugin generates a predictable DOM structure that you can target with CSS.

|!Selector |!Element |
|`.outline` (or your `class`) |The container `<div>` |
|`.level-0` … `.level-10` |Applied to every element; controls indentation |
|`.outline details` |Any collapsible node (group or tiddler item with content) |
|`.outline details[open]` |A currently-expanded node |
|`.outline details > summary` |The clickable row header |
|`.so-arrow` |`<span>` inside `<summary>` holding the rotating arrow icon |
|`.so-label` |`<span>` wrapping the display text inside `<summary>` |
|`.so-toggle` |`<span>` after `.so-label` when `summary-template` is active — empty; useful for custom expand/collapse indicators |
|`.ltgraybox` |`<div>` wrapping expanded tiddler content |
|`div.item` |Non-expandable tiddler reference (tiddler has no body) |
|`.outline h2` |Section header |

To replace the default arrow with your own indicator:

```css
/* hide the default arrow */
.my-outline .so-arrow { display: none !important; }

/* use .so-toggle to show + / – instead */
.my-outline details > summary .so-toggle::before { content: "+"; }
.my-outline details[open] > summary .so-toggle::before { content: "−"; }
```

!! summary-template

When set, the named tiddler is rendered inside each `<summary>` element instead of plain text.  Two variables are available: `<<currentTiddler>>` (the item's tiddler title) and `<<so-label>>` (the pre-computed display label).

Example template tiddler:

```
<span class="so-label"><<so-label>></span><span class="so-toggle"></span>
```

Usage:

```
<$simple-outline text={{MyOutline}} class="my-outline"
  summary-template="My Summary Template"/>
```

!! detail-template

When set, the named tiddler is rendered as the expanded content for each item instead of transcluding the tiddler's body directly.  The same two variables are available.

Example template tiddler — adds a linked title above the body:

```
<$link to=<<currentTiddler>> class="so-detail-title"><<currentTiddler>></$link>
<$transclude $tiddler=<<currentTiddler>> $mode="block"/>
```

CSS for the linked title:

```css
.outline .so-detail-title {
    display: block;
    font-weight: bold;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #aac;
    margin-bottom: 0.4em;
}
```

Usage:

```
<$simple-outline text={{MyOutline}} class="outline"
  detail-template="My Detail Template"/>
```
